04543nam a22005775i 9780773548497DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2016497898  a97807735484977 a10.1515/97807735484972doi  a(DE-B1597)657374  a(OCoLC)965737646  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aB105.W3bC67 2016 4aU102.C6643bC676 2016eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a172/.422231 aCormier, Youri, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar as Paradox :bClausewitz and Hegel on Fighting Doctrines and Ethics /cYouri Cormier. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v6700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote -- tIntroduction -- tHow to Approach Claims That Hegel and Clausewitz Generate Self-Fulfilling Prophecies and War Mongering -- tPerfection and Certainty in Metaphysics and War Theory -- tClausewitz’s Scepticism: The First Dialectical Moment -- tThe Decay and Resilience of Positive Doctrines from Jomini to the Twentieth Century -- tReal and Absolute War: The Second Dialectical Moment -- tTransitioning from Kantianism to Hegelianism -- tThe Unresolved Ethical Impasse in Dialectical War Theory -- tFraming War as a Right: The “Actualization” of Freedom -- tClausewitz and Hegel: Where the Convergence on Method Begins -- tClausewitz and Hegel: The Convergence Peaks in On War’s Book I, Chapter 1, as the Divergence on Ethics Sharpens -- tFighting Doctrines and Revolutionary Ethics -- tEpilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwo centuries after Carl von Clausewitz wrote On War, it lines the shelves of military colleges around the world and even showed up in an Al Qaeda hideout. Though it has shaped much of the common parlance on the subject, On War is perceived by many as a “metaphysical fog,” widely known but hardly read. In War as Paradox, Youri Cormier lifts the fog on this iconic work by explaining its philosophical underpinnings. Building up a genealogy of dialectical war theory and integrating Hegel with Clausewitz as a co-founders of the method, Cormier uncovers a common logic that shaped the fighting doctrines and ethics of modern war. He explains how Hegel and Clausewitz converged on method, but nonetheless arrived at opposite ethics and military doctrines. Ultimately, Cormier seeks out the limits to dialectical war theory and explores the greater paradoxes the method reveals: can so-called “rational” theories of war hold up under the pressures of irrational propositions, such as lone-wolf attacks, the circular logic of a “war to end all wars,” or the apparent folly of mutually assured destruction? Since the Second World War, commentators have described war as obsolete. War as Paradox argues that dialectical war theory may be the key to understanding why, despite this, it continues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWar (Philosophy) 0aWar (Philosophy). 0aWarxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077354849740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773548497423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773548497/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles